<h1>API Reference</h1>

<p>This section is for developers building on top of grigson — implementing a custom renderer, integrating the parser into a tool, or working with the programmatic APIs.</p>
<p>If you want to write chord charts and render them in a web page, start with the <a href="{{ '/language/' | url }}">Language</a> reference and <a href="{{ '/renderers/' | url }}">Renderers</a> instead.</p>

<hr>

<h2>Renderer interface</h2>
<ul>
  <li><a href="{{ '/api/renderer-interface/' | url }}">Renderer Interface</a> — how to implement a custom renderer; the song tree structure</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>Programmatic APIs</h2>
<ul>
  <li><a href="{{ '/api/transpose/' | url }}">Transpose</a> — <code>transposeSection</code>, <code>transposeSong</code>, <code>transposeSongToKey</code></li>
  <li><a href="{{ '/api/harmonic-analysis/' | url }}">Harmonic Analysis</a> — <code>analyseHarmony</code>; ii-V-I and V-I pattern detection, temporary key inference</li>
  <li><a href="{{ '/api/key-detection/' | url }}">Key Detection</a> — <code>detectKey</code>; infer tonic from a chord sequence</li>
  <li><a href="{{ '/api/validator/' | url }}">Validator</a> — <code>validate</code>; structured diagnostics from a <code>.chart</code> source string</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>Internals</h2>
<ul>
  <li><a href="{{ '/api/time-signatures/' | url }}">Time Signatures</a> — how time signatures flow through the parser, normalizer, and HTML renderer layers</li>
</ul>
